{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a898d367-c382-4359-8619-5c8d5e829420","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compiled and ran without issues. The test confirmed:\n\n- `Span<nint>` — signed native-sized integers (8 bytes on this 64-bit system, so `MaxValue` = `9223372036854775807`)\n- `Span<nuint>` — unsigned native-sized integers (`MaxValue` = `18446744073709551615`)\n\nThis has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint` and `nuint` were introduced as first-class types (aliases for `System.IntPtr` / `System.UIntPtr`). Since they are unmanaged types, they work with `stackalloc` just like `int`, `long`, etc.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b386f311-86cf-4251-b876-b8a94d803cb6","outputTokens":197,"requestId":"6C44:4B97:D276D4:10680A9:6A012965"},"id":"0852f1f9-7713-414d-a359-9a5cc64c8b5c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:57:15.426Z","parentId":"34a57cbd-fdcc-4a53-8023-3a64e73123cc"}
